request.insert-caret: Einu sinni var nakinn Anton, í herbergi sínu að forrita sexy kóða í C#. Sexy kóðinn var orðið veikt en vegna ófærðar komst ekki Anton upp að næsta spítala með kóðann, því ákvað hann að prenta út kóðann, leggja pappírana með útprentaða source kóðanum á rúmið, og kúrði yfir því. Source kóðinn virkaði eftir það svo lengi sem sögur segja.

David Rice is a high school student in Ann Arbor, abandoned by his mother at five, enamored with Millie, a fellow student, and picked on by at least one classmate. On a winter's day, while about to drown, he discovers he can transport himself instantaneously to anyplace on earth. He leaves town, goes to New York City, robs a bank vault, and comes to the attention of a shadowy group of government hunters. Eight years later, the hunters, led by the murderous Roland, get a fix on David. He heads home, searches out Millie, invites her to travel with him, and only later realizes that Roland and his crew are seriously deadly. Is everyone close to David in danger?

Unintended pregnancies include unwanted pregnancies as well as those that are mistimed. Worldwide, 38% of pregnancies are unintended (some 80 million unintended pregnancies each year).[1] Unintended pregnancies result in about 42 million induced abortions per year, and 34 million unintended births.[1]

To me, there's an important message hidden in this film. I feel that the makers of this film wanted to deliver a message. In this genre of film, almost all the "gifted" individuals turned out to be some superhero or saviour of mankind. Like Superman, Spiderman, Batman, Daredevil, X-men, Fantastic 4.. just to name a few.
